Since we are changing the variable from $x$ to $\theta$, we must convert the limits of integration:

**Lower limit ($x = -3$):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
-3 &= 3\sin\theta \\
\sin\theta &= -1 \\
\theta &= -\frac{\pi}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Upper limit ($x = 3$):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
3 &= 3\sin\theta \\
\sin\theta &= 1 \\
\theta &= \frac{\pi}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Now we perform the integration with respect to $\theta$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
A &= \frac{9}{2} \left[ \theta + \frac{1}{2}\sin 2\theta \right]_{-\frac{\pi}{2}}^{\frac{\pi}{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

We evaluate the definite integral by substituting the limits:

$$
\begin{aligned}
A &= \frac{9}{2} \left[ \left(\frac{\pi}{2} + \frac{1}{2}\sin(\pi)\right) - \left(-\frac{\pi}{2} + \frac{1}{2}\sin(-\pi)\right) \right] \\
&= \frac{9}{2} \left[ \left(\frac{\pi}{2} + 0\right) - \left(-\frac{\pi}{2} + 0\right) \right] \\
&= \frac{9}{2} \left[ \pi \right] \\
&= \frac{9\pi}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using the power rule for integration $\int x^n dx = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
V &= \pi \left[ \frac{u^7}{7} + \frac{6u^6}{6} + \frac{9u^5}{5} \right]_{-2}^{0} \\
&= \pi \left[ \frac{u^7}{7} + u^6 + \frac{9u^5}{5} \right]_{-2}^{0}
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally, we find a common denominator (35) to combine the fractions:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{128}{7} &= \frac{640}{35} \\
64 &= \frac{2240}{35} \\
\frac{288}{5} &= \frac{2016}{35}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
V &= \pi \left( \frac{640 - 2240 + 2016}{35} \right) \\
&= \pi \left( \frac{416}{35} \right)
\end{aligned}
$$

$$V = \frac{416\pi}{35}$$
